        <body>
            <head><name type="stone">CIIC 48. <placeName type="findspot">Donard</placeName></name>,
                Co. <placeName type="county">Wicklow</placeName></head>
            <ab><rs>National Monuments Service Record Number: <ref
                        target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=WI021-004----"
                        >WI021-004----</ref>
                </rs></ab>
            <div type="description" n="site type">
                <head>Site Type</head>
                <p>Standing stone pair</p>
            </div>
            <div type="description">
                <head>Description</head>
                <div type="description" n="site description">
                    <head>Site</head>
                    <p>
                        <q>Formerly standing beside another stone (at a distance of 1' 6"),
                            uninscribed, on the farm called Old Mills, south of the village of
                            Donard </q><ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945">
                                    (<bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >52</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>; <ref type="bibliog" target="#COR2002"
                                    >(<bibl><author>Corlett and Weaver</author>
                                <date when="2002">2002</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >541</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. With permission of the landowner, we visited the original site in
                        September 2010 on a scanning trip to the area. It is located at the top of a
                        slope in the south corner of a field south of the farmhouse in
                        the townland of Ballylion Lower. The remaining stone has no visible inscription and is
                        approximately 1.37m high. </p>
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="monument">
                    <head>Monument</head>
                    <p><q>Rectangular block of stone</q>, <rs type="material"/>
                        <rs type="dimensions">
                            <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="height">1.52</measure>m x
                                <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="width">0.69</measure>m x
                                <measure unit="metre" type="length" rend="depth"
                            >0.53</measure>m</rs>
                        <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945">(converted from
                                    <bibl><author>Macalister </author><date when="1945">1945</date>,
                                    <biblScope type="pp">52</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. </p>
                    
                </div>
                <div type="description" n="text">
                    <head>Text</head>
                    <p> up-top <q>dexter angle of main face... The first Q is flaked, and the C is
                            practically worn away</q>
                        <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945">(<bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >52</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>
                        <q>The inscription is much worn and damaged... After it turns on to the top [after KOI] 
                            nothing definite can be stated about the inscription</q>
                        <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1897">(<bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                <date when="1897">1897</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >77</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="ga">
                <head xml:lang="en">Transliteration</head>
                <ab>
                    <lb/><persName><w lemma="IAQINI">IA<unclear reason="damage">Q</unclear>INI</w></persName>
                    <w type="formula" lemma="KOI">KO<unclear reason="damage">I</unclear></w>/
                    <w type="formula" lemma="MAQI"><unclear reason="damage">MAQI</unclear></w>
                    <w type="formula" lemma="MUCOI"><unclear reason="damage">MUC</unclear><supplied reason="lost"
                            >OI</supplied></w>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="ga">
                <head>Translation</head>
                
            </div>
            <div type="figure">
                <head>Images</head>
                <div type="figure" n="three-dimensional-model">
                    <head>3D model</head>
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="photographs">
                    <head>Photographs</head>
                    <p>by <persName><forename>Stephen</forename>
                            <surname>McCullagh</surname></persName>: <lb/>Original site of stone
                        pair with remaining uninscribed stone <lb/>Ogham stone at current location
                        in Donard village</p>
                    
                </div>
                <div type="figure" n="drawings">
                    <head>Drawings</head>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p>The personal name here may be formed from <hi rend="italic">iach</hi>, gen. of <hi rend="italic">éo</hi> 
                        'salmon', plus a diminutive suffix <ref type="bibliog" target="#ZIE1994">(<bibl><author>Ziegler</author>
                            <date when="1994">1994</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >186</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. Hypercorrect Q for C is also found, for example, in 
                        <ref target="search.php?ciic=22">CIIC 40.</ref> INEQAGLAS (Enechglas) <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1991">(<bibl><author>McManus</author>
                            <date when="1991">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                >121-2</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>.</p></item>
                    <item n="2"><p><q>KOI, which is invariably written with the first supplementary
                                character and is alone among formula words in
                                not being attested later, has been explained as a word defining
                                locality, 'here', analogous to HIC IACIT in the British inscriptions
                                though it is never used in these </q>
                            <ref type="bibliog" target="#MCM1991">(<bibl><author>McManus</author>
                                    <date when="1991">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >119</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>.</p></item>
                    <item n="2"><p>cf. <ref target="search.php?ciic=22">CIIC 22. <placeName>Colbinstown</placeName> IV</ref>:
                        <foreign xml:lang="ga">EGNI KOI MAQI MUC[ ... ]</foreign>.
                    </p></item>
                </list>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="locations">
                <head>Locations</head>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Found</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="found">Discovered standing beside another (uninscribed) stone on a
                            farm called 'Old Mills', south of the village of <placeName
                                type="findspot">Donard</placeName>
                            <ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945">(<bibl><author>Macalister</author>
                                    <date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >52</biblScope></bibl></ref>; <ref type="bibliog"
                                target="#COR2002"><bibl><author>Corlett and Weaver</author>
                                    <date when="2002"> 2002</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >541</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>, in townland of Ballylion
                            Lower and barony of Lower Talbotstown. The find location of this stone
                            may be accessed via the <ref
                                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=WI021-081----"
                                >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                                www.archaeology.ie</ref>. (GPS:
                            <geo>-6.633596,53.009083</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Original</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="origLocation">Find location possibly original site</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Last recorded</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="lastLocation"> Located on the village green since 1995, having had
                            three previous locations. The present location of this stone may be
                            accessed via the <ref
                                target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=WI021-004----"
                                >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                                www.archaeology.ie</ref>. (GPS: <geo>-6.613237,53.021622</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="record">
                <head>History of Recording</head>
                <p>Published by <ref type="bibliog" target="#RHY1903"><bibl><author>Rhys</author> 
                    (<date when="1903">1903</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                        >113</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> where he referred to it as <q>The Oldmills Piper Stone</q>.
                </p>
            </div>
